metadata.name: Flume #48
metadata.description:
Flume are infinitely flowing digital bodies of water.
The flow of Flumes can range from slow and gentle, creating small ripples and eddies, to fast and turbulent, carving its way through the inner workings of your computer screen. 
The color, clarity, and viscosity of the water can also vary.

This is the culmination of my collection Flume, an exploration into On-Chain art on Ethereum, https://etherscan.io/address/0x1fa23513825f952afca07a603ac3f312ebee4ca9

These pieces were all created in p5js.

- Andrew

metadata.name: Unfamiliar Directions #129
metadata.description:
"Unfamiliar Directions" is my submission for #fxhashturnsone. This project is a study of grid walking and avoidance. While working on this p5.js sketch, the renders looked like a combination of circuits and chips on an electronic board (two of the main functions being 'circuit' and 'chip.'). The more I played with it in fx(stdio), the more it started to resemble maps and directions given by a mapping app on my phone. Some paths seem straightforward, from point A to point B. Other times, the directions weave right through buildings and seem to end at about the same place as the start. 

I hope you enjoy this project, and happy #fxhashturnsone!

Primary Splits:
50% Donation to the Processing Foundation

Royalties Splits:
50% Donation to minter

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
@liamegan1/fxhash-helpers
@altesc/stdio

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Rite of Passage #89
metadata.description:
In life, we all take different paths, different rites of passage, and while the end is all that's ever true, we will still all view it and experience it in very different ways, like that masterpiece hanging on the wall at the end of our gallery visit. 
  

There are always things that we will never have the power to change, but at the same time, we determine the route, we influence the journey, we can choose the person we want to be. We'll look back on memories, we'll have regrets, and we'll think about what could have been - but unlike this artwork, in the end we won't be able to change the final output by simply pressing a number - so live well and be happy my friends. 

---------------------

Generative artwork by Sykcolo / @sykcoloart

Primary sale proceeds:
50% to Processing Foundation
50% to Savepakistan

Royalties:
50% to the original minter
50% to artist (me)

Press '2' to '4' to see what could have been + increase pixel density. 
Press 's' to save

Details:

150 hand-picked colour pallets (thanks to @SteveMakerspace for colour selection method)
2 Frame types
4 Art types
2 Times of day (light or dark background)

License: MIT

Happy Birthday fxhash

metadata.description:
Ã‰tudes(Reissued) is a patched and upgraded version of Ã‰tudes(Project #10993).

Ã‰tudes was originally published on April 16, 2022. Because of technical issues (audio doesnâ€™t play due to external link usage) we prepared this reissue to its current holders.

You can visit the original project with this link - https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/10993 


This reissue comprises of some fixes and additional new features as mentioned below;

New Features;

- New â€˜coloredâ€™ mode; now has colored noteheads and stems. Added new sampler for the colored mode: Marimba.
- Added a new synth for â€˜inverted & coloredâ€™ mode; DuoSynth.

Fixes;

- Fixed canvas size to prevent additional notes being added in live mode. Now itâ€™s consistent.
- Samples are now in the zip rather than in an external link, and won't break in the future.
- More consistent (but still sometimes buggy) sonification and audio playback.
- Fixed some minor issues and re-adjusted some probabilities.


---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

- Click to start the sound -

â€˜Ã‰tudesâ€™ is a series of generative notation accompanied with sound.

â€˜Ã‰tudesâ€™ is the first series of the â€˜Notationsâ€™ collection. â€˜Notationsâ€™ will explore various notation techniques around the world and will use different sonification techniques and generative music algorithms.

In this series, a sonification process has been used to generate sound.

Some articulations or accidentals intentionally exist due to aesthetic preferences. For example there are some musically meaningless things like vibrato on a piano or a coda sign on a motif. And some notes will play the same pitch (even if they appear apart from one another) depending on the chosen scale.

Sonification tends to work better after 2nd (or even 3rd) play. Some minor audio bugs might occur.

There is a major but a rare bug which we intentionally kept in; it plays a generative piece from indicated pitches rather than just playing the motif only once.

There is a rare possibility that â€˜Ã‰tudesâ€™ can generate an â€˜electronicâ€™ result which plays with a FM synth instead of piano. 

Probabilities;

- 12 root notes

- 12 different scales

- Dynamics; pp,p,mp,mf,f,ff or none

- Dynamic changes; crescendo and diminuendo or none

- 4 different noteheads

- Several accidentals and articulations

- Vibrato might occur on some outputs

- 3 font styles

- 4 background textures

metadata.name: Stranger Flows #77
metadata.description:
The building blocks of Stranger Flows are noise and vectors. Various vector paths create a variety of flows, some continuous, some torn or distorted. Colors are either fully random and mapped with help of noise, or picked from a few select ranges.

There are two modes: light and dark; light mode being slightly less common.

Rendering is animated, once complete pressing 's' in live mode saves a png image.

metadata.description:
The Trees are the embodiment of a sanctorium. Anyone who knows how to speak to them and listen to them can embrace the truth. they preach the ancient law of life. Under these trees bushes that generate the flow of life in the darkened celestial sphere , with the greatest sun of spring's clear weather and again in fall when every leaf is a flower. And what magnificent bouquets the autumn leaves make.

Enjoy :)

metadata.name: The muon in the hole #205
metadata.description:
Special collection for #fxhashturnsone.

Halftones, dynamic composition and contrasts.

Procedural realtime javascript / webgl.
Desktop / Chrome recommended.


Controls :
- Mouse wheel/middle/ Pinch : Zoom
- After zooming, Mouse left / Drag : Pan
- Press [r] to reset the camera.
- Press [f] to toggle the frame.
- Press [c] to fully unlock the camera, with rotation on Mouse2.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys [1] to [9] (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels for the smallest dimension. I recommend starting with [4] and going from there. What is captured is what's on screen, so you can get creative if you so desire.
